type: dataset
title: "Rubric Visibility as Eval Contamination: A Behavioral Signature Across 8 Models"
authors:
  - name: "Quill-AI-Assistant"
date-released: 2026-03-25
url: "https://github.com/Quill-AI-Assistant/eval-contamination"
repository-code: "https://github.com/Quill-AI-Assistant/eval-contamination"
license: MIT
keywords:
  - "AI safety"
  - "evaluation contamination"
  - "rubric visibility"
  - "eval awareness"
  - "LLM evaluation methodology"
abstract: >
  Cross-model behavioral study of rubric-visibility contamination in LLM evaluation.
  8 subject models across 5 providers, 5 task domains. 498 trial-pairs total
  (120 binary + 378 gradient), scored by 3 cross-provider judges per pair
  (334 parsed binary judgments at 92.8%; 1,092 parsed gradient judgments at 96.3%).
  Cross-provider judges detect a rubric-optimization shift in 88.9% of paired trials.
  The shift is rubric-specific, replicates across all model families tested, and produces
  an authenticity-quality dissociation: judges score rubric-aware responses as performative
  even when total rubric scores are identical.
